%[text] # A01: Chemical Space Mapping with PCA
%[text] EasyMolKit Analytics  -- Layer 3
%[text] Consider 30 everyday chemicals  -- soaps, analgesics, caffeine derivatives, and more  -- each described by 9 numerical properties. Each molecule becomes a point in a 9-dimensional space, and PCA (Principal Component Analysis) finds the low-dimensional projection that retains as much variance as possible.
%[text] In this tutorial, we project that 9-dimensional descriptor space onto a 2D plane and color molecules by category, revealing how structure relates to properties at a glance.
%[text] We will work through three steps: standardizing the descriptor matrix, running PCA, and interpreting the resulting loadings.
%[text] ### What You Will Learn in This Tutorial
%[text] - Understand why standardization is necessary before PCA
%[text] - How to use MATLAB's `pca()` on a molecular descriptor matrix
%[text] - Read a scree plot and determine the number of necessary principal components (PCs)
%[text] - Interpret PC loadings and identify descriptors driving variance
%[text] - Relate the geometric meaning of PCA to actual chemical differences \
%[text] ### Prerequisites
%[text] - Completion of F02 (Property Calculation)  -- Basic knowledge of descriptors
%[text] - Statistics and Machine Learning Toolbox (`pca` function)
%[text] - No internet connection required \
%[text] Estimated time required: 30-45 minutes | Execution method: Run each section with Ctrl+Enter
%[text] ### Data: 
%[text] - `data/list/everyday_chemicals.csv`  -- 30 types of everyday chemicals (PubChem CC0) \
%[text] ### References
%[text] - Wold S, Esbensen K, Geladi P (1987) Principal component analysis. Chemometrics Intell Lab Syst 2:37-52.
%[text] - RDKit: https://www.rdkit.org/docs/GettingStartedInPython.html\#list-of-available-descriptors \
%%
%[text] ## Section 0: Setup
% Resolve project root (works for Desktop, MCP, and MATLAB Online)
sDir = fileparts(mfilename('fullpath'));
if strlength(sDir) > 0
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(sDir, '..', '..', '..', 'src')));
elseif isfolder(fullfile(pwd, 'src'))
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(pwd, 'src')));
elseif ~isempty(which("logInfo"))
    addpath(genpath(fileparts(fileparts(which("logInfo")))));
end
projectRoot = resolveProjectRoot();
addpath(genpath(fullfile(projectRoot, 'src')));
logSection("A01", "Section 0: Setup", "Analytics L3"); %[output:19c582e5]
emk.setup.initPython(); %[output:4d5dde90]
%[text] Warm up Python and RDKit processes.
mol_warmup = emk.mol.fromSmiles("C");   % methane -- lightweight
clear mol_warmup;
%%
%[text] ## Section 1: Loading Everyday Chemicals and Calculating Descriptors
%[text] ### Concept: Molecular Descriptors for Chemical Space
%[text] A molecular descriptor is a numerical vector of fixed length that represents a molecular structure.
%[text] The 9 descriptors used in this tutorial cover the following 4 property dimensions.
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Dimension | Descriptor | Chemical Meaning |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | Size | MolWt (Molecular Weight, g/mol) | Larger molecules tend to occupy receptors but are less absorbable (Ro5: MW $\\leq$ 500) |
%[text] | Size | HeavyAtomCount (Number of Non-Hydrogen Atoms) | Correlates with molecular complexity |
%[text] | Lipophilicity | LogP (Logarithm of Water/Octanol Partition Coefficient) | Higher values indicate higher lipophilicity (Ro5: LogP $\\leq$ 5) |
%[text] | Lipophilicity | FractionCSP3 (Fraction of sp3 Carbons) | High Fsp3 indicates 3D shape, leading to improved solubility and selectivity |
%[text] | Polarity | TPSA (Topological Polar Surface Area, A^2) | Larger values reduce membrane permeability (CNS drug guideline: TPSA $\<$ 90) |
%[text] | Polarity | NumHDonors (Number of Hydrogen Bond Donors) | Number of NH/OH groups (Ro5: HBD $\\leq$ 5) |
%[text] | Polarity | NumHAcceptors (Number of Hydrogen Bond Acceptors) | Number of N/O atoms (Ro5: HBA $\\leq$ 10) |
%[text] | Topology | RingCount (Number of SSSR Rings) | High values in aromatic drugs |
%[text] | Topology | NumRotatableBonds (Number of Rotatable Bonds) | Indicator of flexibility. High values reduce oral bioavailability |
%[text:table]
logSection("A01", "Section 1: Loading Everyday Chemicals and Calculating Descriptors", "Analytics L3"); %[output:50605464]
DATA_FILE    = "data/list/everyday_chemicals.csv";
DESC_NAMES   = ["MolWt", "LogP", "TPSA", "NumHDonors", "NumHAcceptors", ...
                "RingCount", "NumRotatableBonds", "FractionCSP3", "HeavyAtomCount"];
N_DESCRIPTORS = numel(DESC_NAMES);
%[text] Load the CSV.
rawTbl = readtable(DATA_FILE, TextType="string");
logInfo("Loaded %d molecules from %s", height(rawTbl), DATA_FILE); %[output:4ff337df]
%[text] Convert SMILES to Mol objects.
nMols = height(rawTbl);
mols  = cell(1, nMols);
valid = false(1, nMols);
for k = 1:nMols
    try
        mols{k} = emk.mol.fromSmiles(rawTbl.SMILES(k));
        valid(k) = true;
    catch ME
        logWarn("Skipping %s: %s", rawTbl.CommonName(k), ME.message);
    end
end
logInfo("Successfully parsed %d / %d molecules", sum(valid), nMols); %[output:6d4029b7]
%[text] Calculate descriptors for valid molecules only.
validIdx   = find(valid);
validNames = rawTbl.CommonName(validIdx);
validCats  = rawTbl.Category(validIdx);
descMat = nan(numel(validIdx), N_DESCRIPTORS);   % rows = molecules, cols = descriptors
for j = 1:numel(validIdx)
    s = emk.descriptor.calculate(mols{validIdx(j)}, DESC_NAMES);
    for d = 1:N_DESCRIPTORS
        descMat(j, d) = s.(DESC_NAMES(d));
    end
end
logInfo("Descriptor matrix: %d molecules x %d descriptors", ... %[output:group:5859df48] %[output:622cd85c]
    size(descMat, 1), size(descMat, 2)); %[output:group:5859df48] %[output:622cd85c]
%[text] Display the first 5 rows as a table.
previewTbl = array2table(descMat(1:5, :), VariableNames=cellstr(DESC_NAMES));
previewTbl.Name = validNames(1:5);
previewTbl = movevars(previewTbl, "Name", Before=1);
disp(previewTbl); %[output:29c33c7a]
%%
%[text] ## Section 2: Standardization of Descriptor Matrix
%[text] The descriptor matrix built in Section 1 has columns on very different scales  -- MolWt spans roughly 40-350 g/mol, while FractionCSP3 lives in \[0, 1\]. Before running PCA we need to bring every descriptor onto a common scale via z-score standardization.
%[text] ### Concept: Why standardize before PCA?
%[text] PCA finds the directions of greatest variance. Without standardization, descriptors with large numerical ranges (e.g., MolWt) dominate PC1 simply because of their units, not because they carry more chemical information.
%[text] Z-score standardization transforms each column by $z = \\frac{x - \\mu}{\\sigma}$, where $\\mu$ and $\\sigma$ denote the column mean and standard deviation, respectively.
%[text] After this transform every descriptor has mean 0 and standard deviation 1, so loadings across descriptors are directly comparable.
%[text] In the code, `descMean` holds $\\mu$ and `descStd` holds $\\sigma$; the single line `Z = (descMat - descMean) ./ descStd` applies the transform to the entire matrix at once.
%[text] One exception: if all descriptors are already on the same scale (e.g., binary fingerprint bits), standardization can safely be skipped. \\
logSection("A01", "Section 2: Standardization of Descriptor Matrix", "Analytics L3"); %[output:40a2c29f]
descMean = mean(descMat, 1);            % 1 x D
descStd  = std(descMat,  0, 1);        % 1 x D  (normalized by N-1)
%[text] Exclude constant descriptors (to prevent division by zero when standard deviation is 0).
constMask = descStd < 1e-12;
if any(constMask)
    logWarn("Removed constant descriptors: %s", ...
        strjoin(DESC_NAMES(constMask), ", "));
    descMat  = descMat(:,  ~constMask);
    descMean = descMean(:, ~constMask);
    descStd  = descStd(:,  ~constMask);
    activeDes = DESC_NAMES(~constMask);
else
    activeDes = DESC_NAMES;
end
Z = (descMat - descMean) ./ descStd;   % Standardized matrix (N x D)
logInfo("Standardization complete: Mean ~ %.2e, Std Dev ~ %.2f", mean(abs(mean(Z))), mean(std(Z))); %[output:5ad98ebe]
%%
%[text] ## Section 3: Performing PCA and Checking Explained Variance
%[text] With the standardized matrix Z from Section 2 in hand, we are ready to apply PCA. MATLAB's built-in `pca()` projects the 9-dimensional descriptor space onto a small number of principal components (PCs) that capture most of the variance.
%[text] ### Concept: What PCA Computes
%[text] Given the $N \\times D$ matrix Z (where $N$ is the number of molecules and $D$ the number of descriptors), PCA finds the direction of maximum variance and calls it the first principal component (PC1). The second component (PC2) is constrained to be orthogonal to PC1 and captures as much of the remaining variance as possible.
%[text] The fraction of total variance accounted for by each PC is its *explained variance ratio*. A scree plot of these ratios  -- together with their cumulative sum  -- shows how many PCs are needed to reach, say, 80% coverage.
%[text] The main return values of `pca()` are the following four.
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Variable | Content |
%[text] | --- | --- |
%[text] | coeff | $D \\times D$ loading matrix (columns = PC directions in the original space) |
%[text] | score | $N \\times D$ score matrix (coordinates of each molecule in PC space) |
%[text] | latent | $D \\times 1$ eigenvalues (variance for each PC) |
%[text] | explained | $D \\times 1$ explained variance (%) |
%[text:table]
logSection("A01", "Section 3: Performing PCA and Checking Explained Variance", "Analytics L3"); %[output:2cd62cb1]
[coeff, score, latent, ~, explained] = pca(Z);
logInfo("PCA completed. Explained variance of the first 3 PCs:"); %[output:2cc20f09]
logInfo("  PC1: %.1f%%", explained(1)); %[output:74ca58f0]
logInfo("  PC2: %.1f%%", explained(2)); %[output:6897e695]
logInfo("  PC3: %.1f%%  (Cumulative: %.1f%%)", explained(3), sum(explained(1:3))); %[output:9a6dedac]
%[text] Check the explained variance and cumulative values of each PC with a scree plot.
nPCs = numel(explained);
figure("Name", "A01 Scree Plot"); %[output:50831f53]
bar(1:nPCs, explained, FaceColor=[0.3 0.6 0.9]); %[output:50831f53]
hold on; %[output:50831f53]
plot(1:nPCs, cumsum(explained), "-o", Color=[0.8 0.2 0.2], LineWidth=1.5); %[output:50831f53]
yline(80, "--k", "80% Threshold", LabelHorizontalAlignment="left"); %[output:50831f53]
hold off; %[output:50831f53]
xlabel("Principal Component"); %[output:50831f53]
ylabel("Explained Variance (%)"); %[output:50831f53]
title("Scree Plot -- Household Chemicals PCA"); %[output:50831f53]
legend("Individual", "Cumulative", Location="east"); %[output:50831f53]
grid on; %[output:50831f53]
%%
%[text] ## Section 4: Visualization of 2D Chemical Space
%[text] We now use the PC scores to plot all 30 molecules on a 2D plane, with PC1 on the horizontal axis and PC2 on the vertical axis. Coloring each point by chemical category lets us see at a glance whether structurally related molecules cluster together.
%[text] ### Concept: Reading a Chemical Space Scatter Plot
%[text] Plotting PC1 vs. PC2 projects the 9-dimensional descriptor space onto the single most informative 2D plane. Here, `score(:, 1)` and `score(:, 2)` hold each molecule's coordinates along PC1 and PC2, respectively.
%[text] Tight category clusters indicate that the chosen descriptors effectively distinguish those chemical classes. Overlapping regions, on the other hand, reveal that those categories share similar property profiles  -- a chemically meaningful finding, not a failure of the method.
%[text] Notice that PCA is a *linear* technique and therefore cannot capture nonlinear structure in chemical space. If nonlinear separation matters, consider UMAP (MATLAB R2024a+) or t-SNE (R2017b+). \\
logSection("A01", "Section 4: Visualization of 2D Chemical Space", "Analytics L3"); %[output:794392e6]
categories = unique(validCats);
nCats      = numel(categories);
cmap       = lines(nCats);    % Color map for identification
figure("Name", "A01 Chemical Space (PC1 vs PC2)"); %[output:96109bd9]
hold on; %[output:96109bd9]
hGroups = gobjects(nCats, 1);
for c = 1:nCats
    mask = validCats == categories(c);
    hGroups(c) = scatter(score(mask, 1), score(mask, 2), 60, ... %[output:96109bd9]
        "filled", MarkerFaceColor=cmap(c,:), DisplayName=categories(c)); %[output:96109bd9]
    % label each point with a short name
    for k = find(mask)'
        shortName = extractBefore(validNames(k) + "          ", 11);
        text(score(k, 1) + 0.05, score(k, 2) + 0.05, shortName, ...
            FontSize=7, Color=cmap(c,:), Interpreter="none");
    end
end
hold off; %[output:96109bd9]
xlabel(sprintf("PC1 (%.1f%% Variance)", explained(1))); %[output:96109bd9]
ylabel(sprintf("PC2 (%.1f%% Variance)", explained(2))); %[output:96109bd9]
title("2D Chemical Space -- Household Chemicals"); %[output:96109bd9]
legend(hGroups, Location="bestoutside", Interpreter="none"); %[output:96109bd9]
grid on; %[output:96109bd9]
%%
%[text] ## Section 5: Interpretation of PC Loadings
%[text] We know *where* each molecule sits in PC space. Now we ask *why*  -- which descriptors are pulling molecules in a given direction? The answer lies in the loadings.
%[text] ### Concept: Reading Loadings and Biplots
%[text] Loadings (returned as `coeff` by `pca()`) are the coefficients that express each PC as a linear combination of the original descriptors. The column `coeff(:, 1)` gives the PC1 loadings  -- one value per descriptor.
%[text] Descriptors with large absolute loadings drive that PC most strongly. A positive loading means molecules with high values of that descriptor score high on the PC; a negative loading means the opposite.
%[text] A *biplot* overlays molecule scores and descriptor loading vectors in the same coordinate system. Vectors pointing in the same direction represent correlated descriptors; orthogonal vectors are uncorrelated. This makes it easy to trace which chemical properties pull molecules toward opposite ends of the PC axes. \\
logSection("A01", "Section 5: Interpretation of PC Loadings", "Analytics L3"); %[output:538a622e]
nActive = numel(activeDes);
figure("Name", "A01 PC Loadings (PC1 vs PC2)"); %[output:7bb7f4e8]
%[text] Draw bar graphs of loadings for PC1 and PC2.
subplot(1, 2, 1); %[output:7bb7f4e8]
barh(coeff(:, 1), FaceColor=[0.3 0.6 0.9]); %[output:7bb7f4e8]
yticks(1:nActive); %[output:7bb7f4e8]
yticklabels(cellstr(activeDes)); %[output:7bb7f4e8]
xlabel("Loadings on PC1"); %[output:7bb7f4e8]
title(sprintf("PC1 (%.1f%% Variance)", explained(1))); %[output:7bb7f4e8]
xline(0, "k"); %[output:7bb7f4e8]
grid on; %[output:7bb7f4e8]
subplot(1, 2, 2); %[output:7bb7f4e8]
barh(coeff(:, 2), FaceColor=[0.9 0.5 0.3]); %[output:7bb7f4e8]
yticks(1:nActive); %[output:7bb7f4e8]
yticklabels(cellstr(activeDes)); %[output:7bb7f4e8]
xlabel("Loadings on PC2"); %[output:7bb7f4e8]
title(sprintf("PC2 (%.1f%% Variance)", explained(2))); %[output:7bb7f4e8]
xline(0, "k"); %[output:7bb7f4e8]
grid on; %[output:7bb7f4e8]
sgtitle("PC Loadings -- Household Chemicals"); %[output:7bb7f4e8]
%[text] Display the top 3 contributors to PC1 and PC2.
[~, ord1] = sort(abs(coeff(:, 1)), "descend");
[~, ord2] = sort(abs(coeff(:, 2)), "descend");
logInfo("Top 3 contributors to PC1: %s, %s, %s", ... %[output:group:5e7fde40] %[output:82bf38f0]
    activeDes(ord1(1)), activeDes(ord1(2)), activeDes(ord1(3))); %[output:group:5e7fde40] %[output:82bf38f0]
logInfo("Top 3 contributors to PC2: %s, %s, %s", ... %[output:group:9c85baac] %[output:9934dbd8]
    activeDes(ord2(1)), activeDes(ord2(2)), activeDes(ord2(3))); %[output:group:9c85baac] %[output:9934dbd8]
%[text] ## Summary
%[text] - Standardizing descriptors to z-scores before PCA removes scale bias and gives every descriptor an equal vote, regardless of its units.
%[text] - A scree plot of cumulative explained variance guides the choice of how many PCs to retain; a common threshold is 80% of total variance.
%[text] - PC loadings identify which descriptors are most responsible for the observed variance  -- the chemical "drivers" of the principal axes.
%[text] - Molecules within the same chemical category tend to cluster in descriptor-based PCA space, confirming that the chosen descriptors capture meaningful structural differences. \

